<% content_for :head do %>
  <style>
    @media print {
      nav, .no-print { display: none !important; }
      body { background: white !important; }
    }
    @keyframes fadeUp {
      from { opacity: 0; transform: translateY(12px); }
      to   { opacity: 1; transform: translateY(0); }
    }
    .fade-up { animation: fadeUp 0.4s ease both; }
    .prose p { margin-bottom: 0.85rem; }
    .prose p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }
  </style>
<% end %>

<div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto py-10 fade-up">

  <%# Back link %>
  <div class="no-print mb-8">
    <%= link_to root_path, class: "inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 text-sm text-white/40 hover:text-white/60 transition-colors" do %>
      <svg class="w-3.5 h-3.5" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5">
        <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M10.5 19.5L3 12m0 0l7.5-7.5M3 12h18" />
      </svg>
      Back
    <% end %>
  </div>

  <%# Header %>
  <div class="mb-10 pb-8 border-b border-zg-border">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-white tracking-tight mb-3">First-Week Activation Loop</h1>
    <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-white/50">Zero Gravity · School Hub · PRD v1.0 · June 2025</p>
  </div>

  <%# Problem %>
  <section class="mb-10 pb-10 border-b border-zg-border">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Problem</h2>
    <div class="prose text-white/70 leading-relaxed space-y-3 text-sm">
      <p>A school signs up for the product and becomes a customer, but the teachers don't activate it.</p>
      <p>The Head of Department buys Zero Gravity's School Hub, but the daily user is a classroom teacher with no spare time for a new tool that they need to learn how to use. If Zero Gravity doesn't earn a place inside a teacher's workflow in the first 7–10 days, it gets set aside and the school won't renew.</p>
      <p>The insight here is that <strong>the buyer and the user are different people.</strong></p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%# Solution %>
  <section class="mb-10 pb-10 border-b border-zg-border">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Solution</h2>
    <div class="prose text-white/70 leading-relaxed space-y-3 text-sm">
      <p>My approach is based on the idea that teachers will change the way they work if instructed and coached by their managers.</p>
      <p>The proposed solution is to build a social accountability loop within the school's hierarchy. Zero Gravity doesn't chase teachers, the Head of Department (HoD) does it for us.</p>
      <p>The idea is that a teacher will be more accountable to the tool if its usage is looped into their reviews and conversations with their manager.</p>
      <p>On top of this, the teacher will also have step-by-step tasks that they need to perform on the first week of using School Hub. These tasks and the usage of the tool is then what we surface to the manager. This also decreases time-to-value, which is strongly linked to higher activation.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%# Market Research %>
  <section class="mb-10 pb-10 border-b border-zg-border">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Market Research</h2>
    <p class="text-sm text-white/70 leading-relaxed mb-5">Market research was performed in order to find successful examples where this implementation increased activation.</p>
    <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-zg-border pl-5 py-1">
      <p class="text-sm text-white/50 italic leading-relaxed">
        The two pillars of the design are each independently well-evidenced:<br>
        (a) Admin/manager usage visibility is the standard playbook for driving account-level adoption (some examples are Nearpod, Clever, Slack and Newsela);<br>
        (b) First-week onboarding checklists reliably lift activation and conversion (Ghost saw a 1,000%+ conversion increase for one cohort; Sked Social tripled conversions).
      </p>
    </blockquote>
  </section>

  <%# Target Audience %>
  <section class="mb-10 pb-10 border-b border-zg-border">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-5">Target Audience</h2>
    <div class="space-y-5">
      <div>
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-white mb-1">Primary: Classroom teacher.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-white/70 leading-relaxed">Time-poor, mildly sceptical of new tools thrust upon them by management. Needs a clear, bounded path to value, not open-ended exploration. Five tasks due for the first week will probably activate more users than an empty screen.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-white mb-1">Secondary: Head of Department.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-white/70 leading-relaxed">More accountable for the ROI of the School Hub, line manager to the teachers who need to be activated. Needs visibility and one simple action. Must feel like a <em>coach</em>, not an auditor.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%# What We're Building %>
  <section class="mb-10 pb-10 border-b border-zg-border">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-6">What We're Building</h2>

    <%# Screen 1 %>
    <div class="mb-8">
      <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-white mb-1">
        Screen 1 · Teacher Task List
        <span class="text-zg-teal font-mono text-sm font-medium ml-1">/t/dash</span>
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-white/70 leading-relaxed mb-4">A personalised first-week checklist replacing the blank dashboard. The goal is for a teacher to be able to complete in under 25 minutes across the week. This gives them small wins and holds their hand through the first few usages of the tool.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-white/60 leading-relaxed mb-5 bg-white/5 border border-zg-border rounded-lg px-4 py-3"><strong>Note:</strong> For this feature, I am assuming all the teacher's classes and students have already been added to the platform as we should get this data when the school becomes a customer.</p>

      <div class="bg-zg-surface border border-zg-border rounded-xl overflow-hidden mb-5">
        <table class="w-full text-sm">
          <thead>
            <tr class="bg-white/5 border-b border-zg-border">
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left text-xs font-semibold text-white/40 uppercase tracking-wide w-8">#</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left text-xs font-semibold text-white/40 uppercase tracking-wide">Task</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left text-xs font-semibold text-white/40 uppercase tracking-wide">Why</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-white/5 text-white/70">
            <tr>
              <td class="px-4 py-3.5 text-white/40 font-medium">1</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3.5">Set up your first class's subject</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3.5 text-white/60">Creates a foundation: the teacher will have the class's curriculum on the system after this step.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="px-4 py-3.5 text-white/40 font-medium">2</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3.5">Assign your first topic</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3.5 text-white/60">Connects the curriculum to the AI tutor <em>(assumption)</em></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="px-4 py-3.5 text-white/40 font-medium">3</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3.5">Check a student's report</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3.5 text-white/60">The first aha moment — real data, real value</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="px-4 py-3.5 text-white/40 font-medium">4</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3.5">Share AI Tutor with students</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3.5 text-white/60">The teacher becomes an advocate, which also improves the value they get from School Hub</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="px-4 py-3.5 text-white/40 font-medium">5</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3.5">Set a weekly check-in reminder</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3.5 text-white/60">Converts a one-off into a habit: the actual retention mechanism</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="text-sm text-white/70 leading-relaxed space-y-2">
        <p>Progress bar at the top (turns green at 5/5). Task completion must feel dynamic and gamified. Footer copy reads: <em>"Your HoD can see your progress"</em>. This does 2 things: shows that we're transparent with the teacher and adds a bit of pressure for them to use School Hub.</p>
        <p>We can also add daily email reminders to teachers who have 0 progress.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <%# Screen 2 %>
    <div>
      <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-white mb-2">
        Screen 2 · HoD Dashboard
        <span class="text-zg-teal font-mono text-sm font-medium ml-1">/hod/dash</span>
      </h3>
      <div class="text-sm text-white/70 leading-relaxed space-y-2">
        <p>A table of every teacher in the department: name, task progress (X/5), last active, status badge (Activated / In progress / Not started), and a <strong>one-click nudge button.</strong> Three summary stat cards at the top. No content of individual tasks is visible, only the completion state.</p>
        <p><strong>Copy principle:</strong> <em>"Help your team get set up"</em>; not: <em>"Track your team's compliance."</em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%# What We Deliberately Cut %>
  <section class="mb-10 pb-10 border-b border-zg-border">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-5">What We Deliberately Cut</h2>
    <div class="bg-zg-surface border border-zg-border rounded-xl overflow-hidden">
      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="bg-white/5 border-b border-zg-border">
            <th class="px-5 py-3 text-left text-xs font-semibold text-white/40 uppercase tracking-wide">Cut</th>
            <th class="px-5 py-3 text-left text-xs font-semibold text-white/40 uppercase tracking-wide">Reasoning</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="divide-y divide-white/5 text-white/70">
          <tr>
            <td class="px-5 py-3.5 whitespace-nowrap">Real auth / SSO</td>
            <td class="px-5 py-3.5 text-white/60">Days of setup, zero product insight for the demo</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="px-5 py-3.5 whitespace-nowrap">Email delivery</td>
            <td class="px-5 py-3.5 text-white/60">Toast + state change proves the concept; infra is solved</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="px-5 py-3.5 whitespace-nowrap">Multi-department views</td>
            <td class="px-5 py-3.5 text-white/60">Model already supports it: scope protects demo quality</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="px-5 py-3.5 whitespace-nowrap">Historical analytics</td>
            <td class="px-5 py-3.5 text-white/60">Build it when teachers are retained, not to get them there</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="px-5 py-3.5 whitespace-nowrap">Full class management</td>
            <td class="px-5 py-3.5 text-white/60">The teacher needs a reason to log in, not an admin suite on day 1</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%# GTM Angle %>
  <section class="mb-10 pb-10 border-b border-zg-border">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-4">GTM Angle</h2>
    <p class="text-sm text-white/70 leading-relaxed">The HoD dashboard is also a sales asset. During the school sales cycle, showing a prospective HoD "here's how you'll know it's working" shifts the conversation from a features pitch to an accountability conversation, where HoDs live. Activation visibility also creates a natural expansion vector: once a department is active, show the HoD a cross-department view.</p>
  </section>

  <%# Potential Risk %>
  <section class="mb-10 pb-10 border-b border-zg-border">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Potential Risk</h2>
    <p class="text-sm text-white/70 leading-relaxed">That teachers complete the checklist <em>because their HoD can see it</em>, not despite it. If the framing reads as surveillance rather than support, the feature might produce resentment. Test this with a two-variant HoD dashboard: coaching language vs. compliance language. Measure task completion rate and teacher NPS per variant.</p>
  </section>

  <%# Success Metrics %>
  <section class="mb-10 pb-10 border-b border-zg-border">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Success Metrics</h2>
    <div class="text-sm text-white/70 leading-relaxed space-y-2 mb-5">
      <p>Week-1 task completion rate per teacher, segmented by whether their HoD viewed the dashboard that week and also segmented by HoD who nudged. <em>A significant gap proves the accountability loop works.</em></p>
      <p>We should also A/B test the tasks themselves against an empty dashboard. <em>Do the tasks increase activation?</em></p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-zg-surface border border-zg-border rounded-xl overflow-hidden">
      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="bg-white/5 border-b border-zg-border">
            <th class="px-5 py-3 text-left text-xs font-semibold text-white/40 uppercase tracking-wide">Metric</th>
            <th class="px-5 py-3 text-left text-xs font-semibold text-white/40 uppercase tracking-wide">Target</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="divide-y divide-white/5 text-white/70">
          <tr>
            <td class="px-5 py-3.5">Teachers completing 5/5 tasks in week 1</td>
            <td class="px-5 py-3.5 font-semibold text-zg-teal">&gt;60%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="px-5 py-3.5">HoDs opening the dashboard in week 1</td>
            <td class="px-5 py-3.5 font-semibold text-zg-teal">&gt;80%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="px-5 py-3.5">Completion rate gap: HoD-viewed vs. not</td>
            <td class="px-5 py-3.5 font-semibold text-zg-teal">&gt;20pp</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="px-5 py-3.5">Nudge-to-completion rate (within 48h)</td>
            <td class="px-5 py-3.5 font-semibold text-zg-teal">&gt;40%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="px-5 py-3.5">30-day weekly login retention (activated teachers)</td>
            <td class="px-5 py-3.5 font-semibold text-zg-teal">&gt;50%</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%# How AI Was Used %>
  <section class="mb-10 pb-10 border-b border-zg-border">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-4">How AI Was Used</h2>
    <div class="text-sm text-white/70 leading-relaxed space-y-3">
      <p><strong>AI handled (~80%):</strong> Rails scaffolding, migrations, model associations, seed data, Tailwind components, controller boilerplate, the nudge toast interaction, and view logic.</p>
      <p><strong>I stepped in (~20%):</strong> The core strategy and product idea were human reasoning using AI to assist on the development of the final idea.</p>
      <p>The HoD dashboard framing (coach vs. monitor) went through multiple correction passes; Edge cases in the activation status logic (<code class="bg-white/10 px-1 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">nil last_login_at</code>, zero-division on task count) needed hands-on debugging after reviewing AI output.</p>
      <p>AI was also used for a first draft of this document, which was then reviewed and edited.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%# Assumptions %>
  <section class="mb-10">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Assumptions</h2>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-white/70">
      <% [
        "Teachers have at least ~30 minutes of unstructured time during their first week to engage with a new tool",
        "A teacher who completes all 5 tasks in week 1 is a leading indicator of long-term retention, not just a vanity metric",
        "The HoD will check the dashboard at least once in the first two weeks without being prompted",
        "The HoD has enough social capital and influence with their team that a nudge feels supportive",
        "Five tasks is the right scope: too few and there's no sense of progress, too many and it becomes a burden",
        "The tasks added are all assumptions about what seems reasonable for School Hub tasks",
        "\"Last login\" and total time on app are meaningful proxies for engagement",
        "Zero Gravity has been introduced to teachers by the HoD before they land on the dashboard"
      ].each do |item| %>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="mt-1.5 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-white/40 flex-shrink-0"></span>
          <span class="leading-relaxed"><%= item %></span>
        </li>
      <% end %>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <%# Footer %>
  <div class="pt-8 border-t border-zg-border flex items-center justify-between">
    <div>
      <p class="font-semibold text-white">Zero Gravity</p>
      <p class="text-xs text-white/40 mt-0.5">School Hub · PRD v1.0 · June 2025</p>
    </div>
    <div class="no-print flex items-center gap-4">
      <%= link_to teacher_dashboard_path, class: "text-xs text-zg-teal font-medium hover:underline" do %>
        Open Teacher demo →
      <% end %>
      <%= link_to hod_dashboard_path, class: "text-xs text-zg-teal font-medium hover:underline" do %>
        Open HoD demo →
      <% end %>
    </div>
  </div>

</div>
